184. Clin J Oncol Nurs. 2018 Aug 1;22(4):377-380. doi: 10.1188/18.CJON.377-380.Bibliotherapy: Appraisal of Evidence for Patients Diagnosed With Cancer.Malibiran R(1), Tariman JD(1), Amer K(1).Author information: (1)DePaul University.An appraisal of the evidence on the efficacy of bibliotherapy on anxiety,distress, and coping in patients with cancer is lacking in the literature.Bibliotherapy is a self-help intervention using a variety of tools, such asself-help workbooks, pamphlets, novels, and audiobooks, to improve mental health.This review identified nine original research articles that examinedbibliotherapy as an intervention to alleviate the psychological issues associatedwith a cancer diagnosis. Data synthesis from these studies provides preliminaryevidence that bibliotherapy is an acceptable and beneficial adjunct therapy forpatients with cancer experiencing anxiety, depression, and ineffective coping.DOI: 10.1188/18.CJON.377-380 PMID: 30035795 